A '''shoulder tap''' is an act in which a minor asks an adult to purchase [[alcoholic beverage|alcohol]] for him or her. Typically, the minor will walk around a [[convenience store]] and solicit help from a passing adult stranger. This is also commonly known as a "Hey Mister".{{citation needed|date=June 2012}}

A [[Los Angeles Police Department]] survey indicated that almost half of minors who attempt to acquire alcohol use this 
method.<ref>http://www.abc.ca.gov/forms/ABC509.pdf</ref> Such communities use [[sting operation]]s to deter adult assistance and promote awareness of the legal consequences of helping [[underage drinking|minors obtain alcohol]].<ref>http://www.abc.ca.gov/forms/ABC511.pdf</ref> 

In 2001, a [[Mothers Against Drunk Driving]] (MADD) chapter conducted a small unscientific study in [[Massachusetts]], in which teens stood in front of 15 stores and asked 100 adults apparently over the age of 21 to buy them alcohol. Eighty-three of the 100 adults refused and 17 agreed.<ref>"MADD sting shows it's easy for minors to get booze", ''[[Boston Herald]]'', May 23, 2001.</ref>

In Central Scotland the practice in commonly referred to as a "jump-in".

